03335nam a22004455i 9780773572645DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735726457 a10.1515/97807735726452doi  a(DE-B1597)657771  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTT26 ǂb A44 2005eb 7aART0150402bisacsh04a745/.0971/090461 aAlfoldy, Sandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrafting Identity :bThe Development of Professional Fine Craft in Canada /cSandra Alfoldy. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b42 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgment -- tIntroduction -- tPioneering Professional Craft in Canada -- tAileen Osborn Webb and the American Craft Council: Establishing a Professional Craft Ideology -- t1967: A Centennial Year of Crafts in Canada and a Leadership Role for Native Crafts -- tProfessional Education, Professional Aesthetics -- tThe Dis/Unity of Craft: In Praise of Hands, Toronto, 1974 -- tThe Professional Ascendancy of the Crafts -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy contrasting American experience with the Canadian context, which includes a unique Quebec identity and a Native dimension, Sandra Alfoldy argues that the development of organizations, advanced education for craftspeople, and exhibition and promotional opportunities have contributed to the distinct evolution of professional craft in Canada over the past forty years. Alfoldy focuses on 1964-74 and the debates over distinctions between professional, self-taught, and amateur craftspeople and between one-of-a-kind and traditional craft objects. She deals extensively with key people and events, including American philanthropist Aileen Osborn Webb and Canadian philanthropist Joan Chalmers, the foundation of the World Crafts Council (1964) and the Canadian Crafts Council (1974), the Canadian Fine Crafts exhibition at Expo 67, and the In Praise of Hands exhibition of 1974. Drawing upon a wealth of previously unexploited materials, this richly documented survey includes descriptions and illustrations of significant works and identifies the challenges that lie ahead for professional crafts in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357264540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773572645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773572645/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles